"There has been a lot of talk recently about ‘parceling’ or ‘parcel mule scams’ whose victims are ‘mules’ who pass on goods acquired with dirty money. Parceling is a variant of ‘money mule scams’, differing from them in terms of dynamics and type of ‘hook’ (job offers, dating services, or even fake charitable organisations that ask the victim to help transfer merchandise). In the early years of digital investigation, the field was dominated by ‘one-man bands’ – solitary professionals with vertical training in specific areas of computer forensics, performing general analyses in areas such as child pornography or petty fraud. As time went on, however, fraudsters displayed new and far-ranging inventiveness, eliciting the need for broad-based teams who could ensure faster reaction times. The current state of the art entails developing investigation protocols and specific investigative expertise for each category of fraud. Regular Computer Fraud & Security columnist Dario Forte provides an overview of the most common types of illicit behaviours and the respective response methods."
